\begin_layout Subsection
Estimated values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,q\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to check how well the linearized ARZ model fits actual data, one
 choses a bounded domain and compares the theoretical solution given by
 the second order model and the data observed.
 Here we focus one the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 as they correspond to the setup that is the most worth studying.
 It is also the most directly practical for control.
 Now that estimates of the actual values of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 have been designed, they will be used to compute fundamental diagrams and
 mapped on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,T\right]\times\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

 domain.
 Fundamental diagrams will then yield estimates of the eigen values 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 that are crucial in this study.
 Finally, predicted values of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 will be compared to their measured counterparts which will allow the computatio
n of a fit error.
 Based on the estimation of this error for different values of the parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, the value offering the smallest error will be used as an estimate.
 Plotting maps of both the predicted values and the observed one will also
 highlight the phenomena the linearized model accounts for and those it
 cannot characterize.
\end_layout

