\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calibration of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

, linearization point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=v^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=Q'\left(v^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

 therefore the calibration of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 consists in finding a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 around which the fundamental diagram 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,q\right)$
\end_inset

 will be linearized.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 will consist in the estimated slope of the fundamental diagram.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 is estimated with a standard 
\begin_inset Formula $OLS$
\end_inset

 method.
 As the data set above only corresponds to the congested regime and the
 fundamental diagram is almost affine as noted above, this estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\lambda}_{2}$
\end_inset

 should be convergent.
 However, the method is only heuristic for now as the samples used in the
 linear regression are obviously correlated.
 They indeed belong to cars travelling in the very same region of the highway
 at the same time.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The method used here is therefore quite straightforward.
 The estimator for 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}$
\end_inset

 is chosen as the empirical mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{v}_{i,j}$
\end_inset

