\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\lambda}_{1}=\widehat{v}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 A linear model is fitted: 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{q}^{count}=b_{1}\widehat{v}+b_{0}+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 represents the noise in the model that would ideally be centered, homoschedasti
c and uncorelated but is not practically) and the estimator for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\lambda}_{2}=\widehat{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

 is estimated by the empirical average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{q}^{count}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{*}$
\end_inset

 by the ratio of the estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Provided each estimator is convergent, the continuity of the functional
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\rightarrow\frac{x}{y}$
\end_inset

 on its domain guarantees the convergence of the estimator for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The empirical results for are presented on Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Calibration-of-eigen-values"

\end_inset

.
 The determination coefficient is rather mediocre, it could be improved
 by filtering out outliers and points corresponding to low values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 which could belong to the free-flowing part of the fundamental diagram.
 Improving the quality of the estimation will be the subject of further
 work on that matter.
 Significance tests for the coefficients of the linear model are not presented.
 The assumptions they rely on about the noise in the model are clearly not
 respected here as the noise is auto-correlated.
 Again, further work needs to turn this rather heuristic method for esimating
 the parameters of the model into a fully justified statistical procedure.
 This procedure goes beyond the scope of this article whose aim is mainly
 assessing the phenomena that can be accounted for by the linearized second
