\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fourier decomposition of input for a linear PDE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $PDE$
\end_inset

 under scrutiny here is linearized.
 Therefore, decomposing boundary conditions into a sum and then adding the
 simulated values inside the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,T\right]\times\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

 will give the exact predicted values.
 The spectral domain analysis presented above is very useful to that end
 and will be leveraged thanks to Fourier analysis.
 Fourier transform is a linear operator that is practically implemented
 thanks to the Fast Fourier Transform.
 A real signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f\left(t\right)\mid t\in\left[0,T\right]\right\} $
\end_inset

 on one of the boundaries 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(x=0,t\right)\mid t\in\left[0,T\right]\right\} $
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(x=L,t\right)\mid t\in\left[0,T\right]\right\} $
\end_inset

 is transformed into a periodic signal by infinite duplication and then
 turned into a Fourier series 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ t\rightarrow\mu+\sum_{k=1}^{n}\beta_{k}\cdot cos\left(k\cdot wt+\phi_{k}\right)H\mid t\in\left[0,T\right]\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This process is known to be convergent with an infinite sum for any square
 integrable function.
 It is practically extremely accurate in our case.
 Indeed, for any boundary condition, eye inspection cannot distinguish the
 original signal from its Fourier series decomposition.
 In Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Generic-computations"

\end_inset

 the generic way of computing a solution inside the inner domain from a
 Fourier series boundary condition is presented.
 The process is quite straightforward although the necessary computations
 are quite cumbersome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Simulated maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prior to using Fourier decomposed signals and elementary solutions, it is
 necessary to convert the data into the diagonalized basis.
 First of all, the difference with respect to the equilibrium is computed
 for each bucket: 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\widetilde{v}}_{i,j}=\widehat{v}_{i,j}-\widehat{v}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\widetilde{q}}_{i,j}=\widehat{q}_{i,j}-\widehat{q}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Once 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 have been estimated, estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are computed thanks to the following equations: 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\xi}_{1_{i,j}}=\frac{\widehat{\rho}^{*}\widehat{\lambda}_{2}}{\widehat{\lambda}_{1}-\widehat{\lambda}_{2}}\widehat{\widetilde{v}}_{i,j}+\widehat{\widetilde{q}}_{i,j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\xi}_{2_{i,j}}=\frac{\widehat{\rho}^{*}\widehat{\lambda}_{1}}{\widehat{\lambda}_{1}-\widehat{\lambda}_{2}}\widehat{\widetilde{v}}_{i,j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the predicted values for 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 can be computed thanks to the inverse linear transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{q}=\xi_{1}-\frac{\lambda_{1}}{\lambda_{2}}\xi_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{v}=\frac{\lambda_{1}-\lambda_{2}}{\rho^{*}\lambda_{1}}\xi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This procedure gives comparison maps for the data and predicted values
 for both the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,q\right)$
\end_inset

